    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Environment Config and Secrets Separation"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Every Claude application has two categories of runtime configuration: "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "non-secret config",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (app environment name, log level, model version, token limits) and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "secrets",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (API keys, database credentials, signing tokens). These must be stored, accessed, and audited differently. Mixing them \u2014 especially storing secrets in version control alongside config \u2014 is the most common source of API key leaks in production applications."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "The API key is not a config value. It is a credential. Treat every credential with the same care you would give a password, because that is exactly what it is."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This sub-subtopic covers how to classify configuration values, where to store each class, how to load them safely at runtime with fail-fast validation, how to rotate secrets without redeploying the application, and how to detect accidental secret leakage."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
